article.headline: LOS ANGELES 71, HOUSTON 62
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Riding a two-game skid into the home of their
fiercest rival, the Los Angeles Sparks needed someone to shoot them
out of their slump.

The Sparks found two hot hands Tuesday night in Nikki Teasley
and DeLisha Milton.

Teasley went 5-for-5 from beyond the 3-point arc, scoring 18
points, and Milton added 15 to lead the Sparks to a 71-62 victory
over the Houston Comets.

"I haven't been shooting well over the last two games,"
Teasley said. "So I guess they figured to just leave me over
there."

Sheryl Swoopes led Houston with 19 points. Tina Thompson added
15.

Los Angeles (11-2) had lost two straight before holding on for a
sloppy 54-48 win Sunday over Phoenix, the league's worst team. On
this night, however, the Sparks had a much better effort in a
matchup of the only teams in WNBA history to win championships.

The Sparks scored 10 of the game's first 12 points and never
trailed, building a 58-41 cushion with 9:28 left.

Houston (5-6) made a late run and cut the lead to 66-62 on
Swoopes' basket with 1:27 left. Los Angeles responded with a
3-pointer by Milton and a basket by Tamecka Dixon.

"I knew I was going to get open for that play, so all I had to
do was hit it," Milton said. "That was a big shot to hit after we
let them back in it."

Lisa Leslie had 15 points and nine rebounds, and Dixon added 14
points.

Houston's Tiffani Johnson, who sat out the start of the season
with a back injury, made her debut with a basket in 11 minutes.

The Comets lost at home for the first time since May 30.
